Radiocarbon Results 
A 75 mg sample of cotton was extracted by MAET conservators from two separate areas of the cem(: the left side flap at the back of the cemt's head and the right knee. The former, the larger of the two samples, was submitted for radiocarbon dating, while the smaller sample from the knee area was analyzed by Newsom for material identification. The radiocarbon result of 395 ± 27 B .P. (OxA-15359; & 13C =-22.4%0) calibrates with 95 .4 percent confidence to A.D. 1439-1522 (76.7 per­cent), 1574-1584 (l.6 percent) and 1590-1624 
(17.1 percent): of these, the greatest probability lies with the period A.D. 1439-1522. While tradi­tional Tafno lifeways continued for some decades after contact, it is extremely unlikely that this object would have been made as late as 1575-1624: as will b discussed below, such sculptures required an intact indigenous sociopolitical system for their meaning and relevance, and due to population decline and forced acculturation this essential framework disintegrated by the mid-sixteenth cen­tury. Moreover, the piece does not feature any post­contact materials, as seen in other large cotton sculptures, such as the blue glass in both the Pig­orini and Cisneros cemfs, the latter in Europe by ca. 1502. This would suggest that the cotton for the cem{ was collected, and likely spun and woven, some decades prior to, or very shortly after, Euro­pean contact. Cotton fibers (technically, seed hairs or "lint") are produced by the plant on an annual basis, and so represent one year of growth; they are harvested regularly, and hence are an excellent material for radiocarbon dating, as they are not sub­ject to in-built age. Although both raw and spun 

.cotton were stored in cacical "warehouses," as well as people's homes, it is unlikely that they were stored for long periods of time given the constant demand for cotton products, such as hammocks, naguas (skllts), and body ornaments. Hence the date provides a good indication of when the cem{ was constructed. 
