Notes 

1. 
Kerchache (1994:162) considered the elaborately beaded cotton cemf in the collections of the Pigorini Museum, Rome (accession number 4190) a reliquary, but there is no evidence to suggest that it was used in this way: it does not contain any human remains, nor is its construction suggestive of an artifact specifically made to encase bones, as is the case in the Turin cemf. Instead, the Pigorini cemf con­sists of two separate cotton elements-a full sized belt at the base (Biscione 1997: 158), and beaded cemf sculpture at the top, both nailed to a turned wooden base (the latter likely a historic display support). 

